    "reasoning": "First, identify the prime pair (p, q') satisfying the divisibility conditions. Testing small primes, the pair (p, q') = (29, 5) works: 5 divides 29² + 4 = 845 (845/5 = 169) and 29 divides 5² + 4 = 29 (29/29 = 1). For this pair, q² = (p² + 4)/q' = 845/5 = 169, so q = 13 (prime). Thus, k = q - 11 = 13 - 11 = 2.

Next, solve the equation abc + a + b + c = ab + bc + ca + 5. Rewriting, (a - 1)(b - 1)(c - 1) = 4. Substitute x = a - 1, y = b - 1, z = c - 1, so xyz = 4. Minimize a² + b² + c² = (x + 1)² + (y + 1)² + (z + 1)².

Testing symmetric cases and critical points, the minimum occurs when (x, y, z) = (-2, -2, 1) (or permutations), giving (a, b, c) = (-1, -1, 2) (or permutations). The sum of squares is (-1)² + (-1)² + 2² = 1 + 1 + 4 = 6. Other configurations yield higher values, confirming 6 as the minimum.",
